context: The <a2_0><b7_0>northern<b7_0/><a2_0/> side of Miami includes Midtown, a district with a great mix of diversity with many West Indians, Hispanics, European Americans, bohemians, and artists. Edgewater, and Wynwood, are neighborhoods of Midtown and are made up mostly of high-rise residential towers and are home to the <a1_0><b6_0>Adrienne Arsht<b6_0/><a1_0/> Center for the Performing Arts. The wealthier residents usually live in the northeastern part, in Midtown, the Design District, and the Upper East Side, with many sought after 1920s homes and home of the <a3_0><b8_0>MiMo<b8_0/><a3_0/> Historic District, a style of architecture originated in Miami in the 1950s. The northern side of Miami also has notable African American and Caribbean immigrant communities such as <a4_0><b9_0>Little Haiti<b9_0/><a4_0/>, Overtown (home of the <a0_0><b5_0>Lyric<b5_0/><a0_0/> Theater), and Liberty City.
